From: Dustin Kirkland <dustin.kirkland@chainguard.dev>
Subject: [PATCH] fix const-qualifier warnings in string.c

Newer GCC built-ins for strchr()/strstr() propagate const from their
first argument, causing -Werror=discarded-qualifiers on two assignments
in utils/utils/string.c:

  line 33: char *match = strchr(from, *pos)   in translate()
  line 73: found = strstr(str, search)         in strreplace()

In translate(), `match` is only used for pointer arithmetic so declaring
it const char* is correct.

In strreplace(), `found` is later used as a mutable char* (line 87:
pos = found + slen), consistent with the existing (char*) casts already
used in this function (lines 52, 58, 65, 79).  Cast the return value.

--- a/src/libstrongswan/utils/utils/string.c
+++ b/src/libstrongswan/utils/utils/string.c
@@ -29,7 +29,7 @@
 	}
 	while (pos && *pos)
 	{
-		char *match;
+		const char *match;
 		if ((match = strchr(from, *pos)) != NULL)
 		{
 			*pos = to[match - from];
@@ -70,7 +70,7 @@
 	{
 		len = strlen(str);
 	}
-	found = strstr(str, search);
+	found = (char*)strstr(str, search);
 	if (!found)
 	{
 		return (char*)str;
